Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

About Gapminder: Gapminder has collected a lot of information about how people live their lives in different countries, tracked across the years, and on a number of different indicators.

For this project plan, CO2 emission per person will be collected together with GDP per capita (inflation-adjusted), broadband subscribers per 100 people, freedom index, industry percent in GDP, agricultural percent in GDP. Each indicator is stored in a separate excel spreadsheet downloaded on 23rd March 2022. These indicators are merged together in one full dataset.

The variable descriptions below are extracted from the source data.

CO2 emission per person indicates carbon dioxide emission from burning fossil fuels (tonnes per person) (https://cdiac.ess-dive.lbl.gov/).

broadband subscribers per 100 people refers to fixed subscriptions to high-speed access to the public Internet (a TCP/IP connection), at downstream speeds equal to, or greater than, 256 kbit/s. This includes cable modem, DSL, fiber-to-the-home/building, other fixed (wired)-broadband subscriptions, satellite broadband and terrestrial fixed wireless broadband. This total is measured irrespective of the method of payment. It excludes subscriptions that have access to data communications (including the Internet) via mobile-cellular networks. It should include fixed WiMAX and any other fixed wireless technologies. It includes both residential subscriptions and subscriptions for organizations (https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/IT.NET.BBND.P2).

GDP per capita (inflation-adjusted) is gross domestic product divided by midyear population. GDP is the sum of gross value added by all resident producers in the economy plus any product taxes and minus any subsidies not included in the value of the products. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or for depletion and degradation of natural resources. Data are in constant 2015 U.S. dollars https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.KD).

Political rights index / Freedom index (FI) is the average of political rights and civil liberties ratings and is used to determine countries' freedom statuses. It's range on a scale of 1 (most free) to 7 ( least free) (http://gapm.io/dfreedom_fh).

Industry (including construction), value added (% of GDP) Industry (including construction) corresponds to ISIC divisions 05-43 and includes manufacturing (ISIC divisions 10-33). It comprises value added in mining, manufacturing (also reported as a separate subgroup), construction, electricity, water, and gas. Value added is the net output of a sector after adding up all outputs and subtracting intermediate inputs. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or depletion and degradation of natural resources. The origin of value added is determined by the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC), revision 4. Note: For VAB countries, gross value added at factor cost is used as the denominator (https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NV.IND.TOTL.ZS).

Agriculture, forestry, and fishing, value added (% of GDP) Agriculture, forestry, and fishing corresponds to ISIC divisions 1-3 and includes forestry, hunting, and fishing, as well as cultivation of crops and livestock production. Value added is the net output of a sector after adding up all outputs and subtracting intermediate inputs. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or depletion and degradation of natural resources. The origin of value added is determined by the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC), revision 4. Note: For VAB countries, gross value added at factor cost is used as the denominator (https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NV.AGR.TOTL.ZS).

In addition, reference for countries and the continents associated with them are downloaded from https://github.com/dbouquin/IS_608/blob/master/NanosatDB_munging/Countries-Continents.csv

Question(s) for Analysis¶

Question 1: Is the average CO2 per person going up or down between 1998 and 2017? Are there any differences among the continents?

Question 2: Are there any possible correlations found between the CO2 emission per person and other indexes including the GDP per capita, number of broadband subscribers per 100 people, freedom index, percentage of industry contribution to the GDP, and percentage of agriculture contribution to the GDP

import pandas as pd

import numpy as np

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

import seaborn as sn

#read the excel files
co2_per_person = pd.read_excel('co2_emissions_tonnes_per_person.xlsx')
BroadBandSubscriber_per_100ppl = pd.read_excel('broadband_subscribers.xlsx')
gdp_per_Capita = pd.read_excel('gdppercapita_us_inflation_adjusted.xlsx')
freedom_index = pd.read_excel('polrights_fh.xlsx')
industry_GDPpercent = pd.read_excel('industry_percent_of_gdp.xlsx')
agriculture_GDPpercent = pd.read_excel('agriculture_percent_of_gdp.xlsx')
In [155]:
#Restructure the dataset with year as one column in all component datasets
co2_per_person = pd.melt(co2_per_person, id_vars=['country'], value_vars=np.arange(1800,2018,1),var_name='year', value_name='co2_per_person').sort_values(['country','year'])

BroadBandSubscriber_per_100ppl = pd.melt(BroadBandSubscriber_per_100ppl, id_vars=['country'], value_vars=np.arange(1998,2020,1),var_name='year', value_name='BroadbandSubscriber_Per100ppl').sort_values(['country','year'])

gdp_per_Capita = pd.melt(gdp_per_Capita, id_vars=['country'], value_vars=np.arange(1960,2020,1),var_name='year', value_name='gdpPerCapita').sort_values(['country','year'])
freedom_index = pd.melt(freedom_index, id_vars=['country'], value_vars=np.arange(1972,2020,1),var_name='year', value_name='freedom_index').sort_values(['country','year'])
industry_GDPpercent = pd.melt(industry_GDPpercent, id_vars=['country'], value_vars=np.arange(1960,2020,1),var_name='year', value_name='industry_GDPpercent').sort_values(['country','year'])

agriculture_GDPpercent= pd.melt(agriculture_GDPpercent, id_vars=['country'], value_vars=np.arange(1960,2020,1),var_name='year', value_name='agriculture_GDPpercent').sort_values(['country','year'])

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Trends across 156 countries between 1998 and 2017¶

Exploring single variable exploration with function HistogramIt for any year between 1998 and 2017.

Based on the histograms, we can see that the distribution of co2 per person is very skewed to the right in both 1998 and 2017. The most popular amount of CO2 emissions per person most countries fall into is between 0 and 0.5 tonnes per person.

Regarding GDP per capita, between 1998 and 2017, though both histograms are right-skewed, we can see a reduction in the first bucket (0-5000 USD) to the second bucket (5000-10000). This indicates an economic growth in several countries within this time frame.

Regarding freedom index, 1-2 is the most popular, followed by 6-7. Since our range is 1-7, this is quite an extreme distribution, so in most countries, either the rating could be very high in freedom, or very low in freedom. In 2017, the extreme buckets (1-2 and 6-7) reduced in size a little bit with an increase in bucket 3-4 and 4-5 in rating.

Regarding the percentage of industry in GDP, we can see that the distribution is closest to normal distribution among the indexes'distribution. 25-26% of industry in GDP seems to be the most popular among the 156 countries.

Regarding the percentage of service in GDP, the distribution is right-skewed. We can also see that there is a shift to the left of 2017 distribution, as compared with 1998 distribution. This indicates the drop in agriculture contribution to most economies in the world.

In [175]:
#Defining the HistogramIt function to build histograms
def HistogramIt (df,var,bin_interval=0.5,yearx=['1998'],color=['orange']):
    '''
    docstring
    
    Input: 
    df: dataframe that we retrieve data from
    
    yearx: the range of years that we want to look at. the default value is 1998. It receives input in form of array.
    
    var: variable that we want to examine
    
    bin_interval: the width of the bin/ how small or large we want to split the data range to find frequency in each split.
    the default value is 0.5.
    
    color: color of the histogram. The default value is orange. It receives input in form of array.
    
    Output:
    
    a histogram of the variable given by the parameters in the input
    '''
    
    #prepare the plot
    
    fig,ax = plt.subplots(1,figsize=(20,9))
    
    ax.locator_params(integer=True)
    #creating intervals
    
    interval = np.arange(0,df[var].max()+bin_interval,bin_interval)
    
    i = 0
    #histogram
    for y in yearx:
    
        df.query('year=='+y)[var].hist(bins=interval,color=color[i],label = y,alpha=0.5)
    
       
        plt.title('Distribution of ' + var.replace('_',' '))
    
        plt.xlabel(var.title())
    
        plt.ylabel('Frequency'.title())
        
        i = i + 1
    
    plt.legend()

Trend in average CO2 per person for 156 countries between 1998 and 2017

Between 1998 and 2017, the overall world trend is steadily increasing. CO2 per person in Europe, Asia and North America on average are higher than average CO2 per person in all 156 countries, while average CO2 per person in South America, Oceania and Africa are lower than average Co2 per person in all 156 countries. CO2 per person in Europe is on a more noticeable downward trend since 2008, as compared with that in other regions.

Trend in average GDP per capita for 156 countries between 1998 and 2017

There are a lot of fluctuations in the average GDP per capita among 156 countries. This fluctuation can be observed in all continents except for Africa. Interestingly, average GDP per capita in Asia is the closest to average GDP per capita in 156 countries.

Through the chart, we can see that some continents hit the highs and lows differently throughout the years.

Africa is stable with some steady improvements over the year.

Oceania is also stable with only two high hits in 2003 and 2014.

North America, South America and Europe in general has higher average GDP per capita over the years, as compared to the average GDP per capita in 156 countries, except for a few low-years.

Trend in average freedom index for 156 countries between 1998 and 2017

Freedom index development over the years on average for 156 countries does not seem to have much fluctuation. Looking continent-wise, Oceania's freedom index seems to have dropped since 2014. The visualization of the freedom index, especially in the context of continent-wise and comparing with average freedom index in 156 countries, is quite interesting.Average freedom index in Asia tops the chart over the years, and next to Asia is Africa.

Correlation between the indexes¶

Scatter plot is used to explore the correlation between CO2 emission per person and other indexes together with level. Economic level is defined based on the percentile of GDP per capita in a year. Since this economic level is more accurately evaluated on a yearly level, we would look at 2 slices of the data in 1998 and in 2017 to explore the correlations.

The green dots indicate the underdeveloped countries (25th percentile GDP per capita).

The yellow dots indicate the developing countries (50th percentile GDP per capita).

The red dots indicate the developed countries (75th percentile GDP per capita).

The purple dots indicate the very developed countries.

#create function to return relative size for each country data based on GDP
def GDPsizeit(year,ecolevel):
    '''
    input: 
    year: the year that we want to retrieve data from for the GDP per capita
    ecolevel: the economic level that we want to retrieve data from for the GDP per capita
    
    output:
    a list of the GDP per capita values as filtered in input divided by 10 to adjust for the marker size in scatter plot
    '''
    
    
    return full_data_cleaned.query(f'year=={year} and ' + 'economic_level_'+year+ '=="'+ecolevel +'"')['gdpPerCapita']/100

Conclusions¶

Trends

In our analysis for 156 countries between 1998 and 2017:

The overall world trend in CO2 per person is steadily increasing. CO2 per person in Europe, Asia and North America on average are higher than average CO2 per person in all 156 countries. CO2 per person in Europe is on a more noticeable downward trend since 2008, as compared with the index performance in other regions.

There are a lot of fluctuations in the average GDP per capita among 156 countries. This fluctuation can be observed in all continents except for Africa. Interestingly, average GDP per capita in Asia is the closest to average GDP per capita in 156 countries between the years 1998 and 2017.

The freedom index does not have much fluctuation on average for 156 countries over the years. We might need a few more indexes related to political rights and freedom to add more insights to the freedom index from Gapminder. The question here is why continents with more democratic societies have very low rating in freedom indexes. How the samples are collected and how the ratings are designed also affect the result significantly.

Correlation

Based on the scatterplot in 1998 and 2017, we can see that GDP per capita seems to have a positive correlation with CO2 emission per person for very developed countries, developed countries and developing countries. We cannot, however, find correlation between CO2 emission per person with freedom index, agriculture percentage in GDP and industry percentage in GDP. Possible areas for further investigation lie in the underdeveloped countries where GDP per capita does not seem to have any correlation with the CO2 emission per person. It could be that there is a certain threshold in GDP per capita that only above this,we can notice a correlation between these 2 indexes.

We might also need a wider time span (repeated findings in multiple years) to confirm the correlations between CO2 emission per person and other indexes. More efforts can also look into confirming if agriculture percentage in GDP and industry percentage in GDP do not have correlation with CO2 emission per capita. We can also try using other indexes to measure CO2, for example, only total CO2 emission or CO2 emission per USD earned in GDP.

Limitations¶

Several limitations can be summarized below:

The range of time in scope for analysis. We need a wider time scope to confirm and enrich the findings.

The number of countries included in the analysis are limited to 156 countries with available data in the given years.

There are multiple missing values in broadband subscribers per 100 people, resulting in dropping the variable completely from the dataset. Also, missing values in other variables also reduce the sample size for analysis.

The correlation analysis is done in 2 slices of yearly data. There should be confirmed correlations in more years.

Freedom index used in the analysis might be subjected to the ratings and survey design. The index should be compared against other similarly measured indexes in the same category.

No statistical inference was performed in this analysis. This limits any possible generalization conclusion based on the sample data.
